column168: While en-route to the destination facility, the driver was called to confirm a piece count in the trailer, at which time he discovered a drum had a ring of material around the base and he noted a solvent smell.  After notifying his supervisor, he donned a full-face respirator and chemical suit.  He checked the drum closure and he felt that drum should be placed into a salvage drum to ensure proper containment.  He used oil-dry to absorb the solvent and placed that material in the salvage drum as well.  He called back his supervisor to inform that the cleanup and repackaging was complete.  The driver started driving again and began to feel ill a few minutes after the placing the drum in the salvage drum.  He again called his supervisor to inform him of the issue.  Being as he was approaching the port of entry scales at Kemmerer, WY and he was instructed to pull over at that location.  The Lincoln County Sheriff office in Kemmerer was called by the supervisor and requested that they dispatch EMS to assist the ailing driver.  The Sheriff dispatched an ambulance, fire department, and officers to meet the driver.  Also stationed at the scale was WY State Police.  The driver was taken to a local hospital, given oxygen, seen by a doctor and released by the doctor back to duty.  This took about an hour from when he stopped at the scale from when he was released from the hospital.  The fire department allowed the trailer to ventilate the fumes while the driver was at the hospital.  The scale was closed during this period.  After the driver returned to the scale, he confirmed that no other drums had leaked on the load, and continued on.  It was later determined that the gasket on the drum was pinched which allowed a small amount of material to escape.  When the drum arrived at the destination the next day, it was pump into a tank and the drum was crushed prior to disposal.
column169: Actions taken include training with driver to ensure trailers are ventilated prior to entry with a FFAPR when a solvent leak/spill is discovered.  Training will also stress package inspection.

After connecting the hose and opening the valve to start loading the cargo tank the employee observed a leak at the coupling. He began to tighten the coupling and he did not notice that he was unscrewing the coupling on the other end of the hose. The hose came off the coupling releasing crude oil to the ground. It took a few seconds for the employee to shut the valve stopping the flow of crude oil to the ground.    The spill was cleaned up and remediated per the Oklahoma Corporation Commission requirements.
column169: Remind employees that the loading procedures require the loading process to be terminated in case of a leak. Inform them of what happens when you attempt to tighten one end it loosens the other end when the hose is connected and that the hose must be removed to tighten the connections and couplings.

column168: On 03/02/2005 at approximately 1235, a Houston Marine Services (HMS) truck driver started to load trailer #B711 with Pyrolysis Gas Oil (PGO). This transfer was at the HMS Baytown facility's truck loading rack. At approximately 1250 the trailer overflowed spilling 304 gallons of PGO to the concrete containment then to the collection unit. All product was recovered and sent to the HMS Environmental Division. Duration of overflow was approximately one minute.
column169: The HMS truck driver was terminated immediately as this was his second incident involving the same circumstances.

column168: Undeclared Hazardous Materials: Category 6.2/Infectious Substance, Affecting Humans(Salmonella) 1 6-8ml slant of isolated culture, packed and separated from paperwork in a zip-loc bio-bag with no absorbent material.  It was in a small, non-reinforced foam cooler with one identically packed diagnostic fecal-swab.  There was no absorbent, dunnage to secure against sifting, or anything else therein.  The lid was secured by two pieces of scotch-tape.  The "BIOHAZARD(universal)ISOLATION" Sticker was only accompanied by the shipping labels: "WVMC Caldwell, ID" and "To: State Lab Boise, ID"  There are no shipper's papers or waybill.        Along with this cooler, there was the usual cooler from South West District Health Department in Caldwell.  It is a large, plastic-reinforced cooler with a capacity upward of five gallons, and is labeled "Inner Package{sic} Comply with Prescribed Specifications".  There are no addresses present for Shipper or Consignee.         It contained, as always, a mixed content.  There were numerous Diagnostic Specimens(Class 6.2 trade exemption, if properly packaged and labeled)in zip-loc pocketed bio-bags.  {Every Diagnostic Specimen is sent in one of these bags except Tuberculosis Sputum, which is always placed in cans} There were several different sizes of water bottles for the testing of drinking water, and assorted cold-packs.  No absorbent or dunnage was present.  The lid was completely unsecured.       I have notified both of these shippers, and their courier (Action Courier DOT Reg# 808617)on numerous occasions of their violations of 49CFR and Federal HMR.  I have given all parties involved a 15 page print-up from the E-CFR.  I have written them non-compliance letters, which go unheeded.  Their response has been, instead, only complaints to my superiors.  They are, now, knowingly and willfully violating these regulations.        Action courier's driver has responded to verbal notifications with the response, "How do I know that those are dangerous goods?" and, "that's not my responsibility," rebuking my efforts.  I have provided the CFR sections that show him how to meet exemption requirements, and specific articles de-bunking any possible misconceptions held.          Action Courier Service does, currently, have one delivery van that delivers to me daily.  She knows the medical courier exemption, and follows it properly.  I suspect this would be involved in a false claim of practices, and demonstrate criminality by doing so.
column169: Another Courier, Gopher-It, has at least started inspecting packages for proper labeling after notifications.  Some of their customers now, have become less than cooperative.      I will attach images from SCDH in Twin Falls' specimens; received last week.  This shipper has been given the greatest number of notices and has, thankfully, at least ceased her argumentative phone calls:  I would like a second opinion of her claim made in an e-mail:          I appreciate your concern about our packaging of diagnostic samples.  I  have contacted the U.S. DOT representative who told me that our  packaging of diagnostic samples in the overpacks that we have meets  current requirements.  I will keep in touch with them to update our  policies as necessary.    Cheryle Becker, RN  Manager, Communicable Disease Section  South Central District Health  1020 Washington St. N.  Twin Falls, ID 83301

column168: Land Span driver was notified by following vehicle that product was leaking from back of trailer while in transist.  Driver pulled off at next exit to investigate and found paint like substance leaking from rear of trailer.  Upon review of bill of lading, driver opened rear trailer doors to discover 10 5-gallon buckets damaged and 7 1-gallon pales damaged.  The same product was leaking from both of the damaged containers.  Damage had occured because freight loaded to the adjacent right had been improperly blocked and braced and had fallen over on top of the stacked damaged containers.  Land Span immediately contacted shipper and Environmental Management, Inc to assist with contacting professional clean-up crew and coordinating clean-up.  Upon arrival at scene, clean-up crew spent approximately 9 hours isolating damaged containers, repackaging the containers, and thoroughly cleaning the inside and outside of trailer.  Damaged containers were repackaged into 50 gallon drums and loaded onto back of trailer for delivery to consignee.
column169: The damage to containers was a result of improperly securing cargo to prevent falling and also improperly stacking containers onto unsecure surfaces of other containers.  Future incidents could be avoided by better training of dock personel regarding the proper methods for blocking and bracing of hazardous materials as well as more disciplined supervision of the loading of hazardous materials.

On 3/11/2005, 4 portable tanks were loaded on a Triad Transport vehicle at Cypress Semicondutor located in Round Rock, Texas.  The transport vehicle containing the portable tanks arrived at Onyx Environmental Services 10-day intransit facility located in Baytown, Texas on 03/15/2005 at 9:30AM.  Upon arrival at the Onyx facility it was discovered one of the portable tanks had been leaking while in highway transportation.  The cause of the leak was the bung on the top of the portable tank was closed improperly and was missing the gasket required by the closure instructions.  Approximately five gallons of liquid had spilled into the vehicle.  Onyx Environmental Services employees immediately used absorbent to contain the spilled material and all residuals were placed in containers.  A gasket was placed on the bung and the portable tank was properly closed prior to further transportation.
column169: Onyx will discuss the DOT requirement to follow all closure instructions when preparing packages of hazardous materials for shipment with the offeror.

column168: Tank truck stopped in front of house it was to deliver home heating oil to.  Second man got out and was searching around home for fill location while the driver inserted the delivery ticket & engaged the PTO.  Driver got out of truck & noticed that hose (at rear of truck on reel) had ruptured.  Driver notified office to call 911, shut down valves, stopped traffic, and initiated clean-up procedures.  Fire and emergency personnel had responded, detoured traffic, and helped in the completion of the clean-up.  Some fuel was released into a waterway, so the PA Fish Commision was notified.  A spill response team was notified and has since arrived to verify that clean-up was completed correctly.  Rupture was apparently caused by wear in the hose.  Estimated size of tear 1-2". Duration of release approximately 1 minute or less. Our hoses are inspected periodically, but most hoses appear worn from early on, due to the circumstances of their use. This specific hose has been replaced and all drivers are warned to keep the secondary valves at the rear of the truck closed until the time of delivery. Department of Environmental Protection was notified and we will formally meet with them on April 4, 2005 to further investigate the incident.
column169: Drivers have been notified (in writing) to keep all valves closed until time of actual delivery to homeowner.  We will pull all hoses from reel each summer and do a more thorough inspection.  However, pinpointing the time in which a hose must be replaced is not a science.  As stated earlier, a hose can look worn from early on, due to the circumstances of it's use.  We will do our best to visually inspect the hoses upon every use, to prevent further incidents.

driver was driving on hwy 240 11 miles south of Opal, Wy. After coming down a hill, driver was about 1 mile from hill, a gust of wind hit the rocky mountain double, causing the pup trailer in go off the road on to the soft shoulder of road. Trailer then flip and broken away from the other trailer, crack one of the compartment of the trailer, spilling 2200 gallons of diesel fuel on to the shoulder of the road. Once driver stop, driver took a shove to build a containment area to hold the diesel in that area. There were no waterway, sewer, or drainage area around. Spill pads were place on the highway to clean up the diesel on the hwy.
column169: Company has weekly safety meeting. Topic like speeding, accident, and safety issues at talked about. We have our drivers watch video, we have our worker comp. people come in at talk to our driviers. In some meeting, depending on the topic, we give test to the drivers so we make sure they understand what they just learned. Better training would included bring in people from DOT or State Trooper to help educated our drivers. One option we recently expored is sending our driving to a 4 hour defense driving class. Seat Belt Policy and no-answering cell phone policy while driving is in affect at our company. We are looking at setting the govner on the trucks to go no faster than the legal speed limit minus 5 mph. With the help of our insurance company, we have strict guidlines about CDL drivers MVR records.     Move to GPS for all HAZ mat companies. If drivers know the company is watching them, the likely hood for accidents and speeding tickets will be reduced.

column168: I SMELLED H2S UPON ARRIVAL AT MS&CC (6:45 AM).  I CALLED OCC AND REPORTED A H2S LEAK.  GEOFFREY EDELMAN AND I FOUND THE LEAK ON TRAILER T-2 AT 7:15 AM.  THE LIQUID EXCESS FLOW VALVE WAS FROSTED AND LEAKING.  THERE WAS NO HISSING SOUND AND NO LIQUID DRIPPING.  THERE WAS VAPOR LEAKAGE.  RICH FROM EXXONMOBIL CALLED AT 7:15 AM COMPLAINING ABOUT A LEAK (THEY THOUGHT THAT THEY SAW A VAPOR CLOUD).  THE WIND WAS FROM THE SOUTH.  THERE WAS NOT A VISIBLE VAPOR CLOUD.  AFTER WE FOUND NO DAMAGE, WE DETERMINED TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO A LOCATION WHERE WE HAD TOOLS AND STEAM.  GEOFF MOVED T-2 DOWN BY THE H2S LOADING RACK SO WE COULD PUT STEAM ON THE FROSTED VALVE.  THIS NORMAL PROCEDURE WORKED TO ABATE THE LEAK, BUT WE HAD TO BACK OFF THE PACKING AND INJECT ADDITIONAL GREASE TO STOP IT COMPLETELY.  THIS PRODUCED SOME AUDIBLE LEAKAGE FOR THE FIRST TIME.  THE REGREASING WAS SUCCESSFUL.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AT 8:00 AM.  I NOTIFIED OCC (DAVE HOLMES) AND DAVE CALLED EXXONMOBIL (RICH AT EXT. 5332) AT 8:15 AM.  I ALSO NOTIFIED LARRY ZINK BY E-MAIL.  I SPOKE WITH LARRY ZINK LATER IN THE DAY.  WE DISCUSSED THE POSSIBILITY THAT THE PRIOR SERVICE WORK MIGHT HAVE PUT THE INCORRECT GREASE INTO THE PACKING.  I CHECKED THIS OUT AND FOUND THAT THE CORRECT GREASE HAD BEEN USED.  I REPORTED THIS TO LARRY ZINK.  THIS REPORTABLE QUANTITY (100 LBS) FOR FORMAL NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER NOTIFICATION WAS NOT MET.  MY ESTIMATE OF H2S LEAKAGE IS LESS THAN ONE POUND.  NO ONE WAS INJURED AND THERE WAS NO ANY PROPERTY DAMAGE.  WE PUT OUT THE H2S BARRICADES AND USED SAR'S (SUPPLIED AIR RESPIRATORS) TO FIX THE LEAK.  I HAVE INSTRUCTED GEOFFREY EDELMAN TO RE-CHECK T-2 FOR LEAKS LATER TODAY.  HE REPORTED THAT THE TRAILER HAD IN SATISFACTORY CONDITION.
column169: I DO NOT HAVE ANY RECOMMENDATIONS BECAUSE THIS LEAK WAS FOUND IN A TIMELY MANNER, CORRECTED IMMEDIATELY WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column168: UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISCOVERED AND REPORTED BY CONSIGNEE: DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN (6ML SERUM FOR SYPHILIS TESTING)  REPORTING REQUIRED UNDER CODE OF FEDERAL REGULATIONS TITLE 49: 171.16 DETAILED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INCIDENT REPORTS. (A) GENERAL. (4) AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IS DISCOVERED.  (AIR ELIGIBLE/UNDECLARED)  173.199 DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMENS AND USED HEALTH CARE PRODUCTS.  THE SHIPPING CONTAINERS HAD NO LABELS, OTHER THAN PRODUCT INFO (SEE ATTACHED).  IT WAS PLAINLY VISIBLE THROUGH THE WINDOW OF A FEDEX CLINICAL PAK OVER-WRAP, IN WHICH IT WAS SEALED (ALSO ATTACHED).  THERE ARE SEVERAL INDICATORS OF CONCEALED DANGEROUS GOODS THAT WOULD HAVE BEEN DETECTED BY THE CARRIER, IF SCREEN-OUT PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED PROPERLY:  1. THIS MODEL OF FEDEX-PAK IS USED AND ISSUED BY FEDEX TO PROVIDE ADDITIONAL PROTECTIVE FROM PACKAGE LEAKAGE.  IT HAS A PROMINENT DISCLAIMER NOTICE, AND A BOX FOR SHIPPERS TO MARK, STATING DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN WITH IATA COMPLIANCE.  2.  THE SHIPPING LABEL ON THE OVER-WRAP HAS, IN THE SHIP-TO ADDRESS REFERENCE FIELD, THE PHRASE "MEDICAL SPECIMENS."  THIS IS NEITHER A PROPER SHIPPING NAME, NOR IS IT OF SUFFICIENT SIZE OR LOCATION TO BE REASONABLY CONSIDERED A "LABEL" FOR JUDGING THIS A MISCLASSIFICATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS, INSTEAD.  IT WOULD HAVE ASSISTED HOWEVER, UPON CLOSER EXAMINATION AS A SCREEN-OUT FACTOR.  3.  THIS PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP AT A KNOWN MEDICAL LABORATORY FACILITY BY FEDEX.  IT IS, CLEARLY, IN THEIR CUSTOMER'S BUSINESS NAME.
column169: THIS SHIPPER, UNARGUABLY, IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THIS INCIDENT.  HOWEVER, IT SHOULD NOT HAVE GONE UNDETECTED UNTIL FINAL DELIVERY.  THE EXCEPTIONS FROM FULL-SURFACE REGULATION GRANTED DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMENS, UNDER INDUSTRY, FINANCIAL, AND PUBLIC HEALTH TESTING NEEDS, HAS ALLOWED MANY SHIPPERS TO DISREGARD THE REMAINDER.  THE LESSER REQUIREMENTS FOR INCIDENT REPORTING, IN PARTICULAR, UNDERMINE THE ABILITY OF REGULATORS TO ACCURATELY JUDGE CURRENT SAFETY LIABILITIES.  IF THE ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS ARE TO BE MET FOR AIR ELIGIBLE DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMENS, FOR THAT REASON ALONE, A GREATER LEVEL OF DUE DILIGENCE IS NEEDED FROM THEIR CARRIERS.  PURSUANT TO SAFETY LIABILITY ASSESSMENT, AND ONLY THROUGH PROPER PROCEDURE, INVESTIGATION INTO THE RESULTS OF TESTING DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMENS REPORTED UNDECLARED MAY ALSO PROVE INFORMATIVE.

column168: On the morning of March 2, 2005 at approximately 0630 from our driver reporting that he had hydrochloric acid leaking from a 330 gallon IBC on his truck.  We contacted Hanover Fire Department immediately.  Our personnel arrived on scene at approximately 0715 and began determining other materials on the vechicle.  We then called IMS Environmental Services and notified them of the incident and asked for a response team to assist.  Hanover FD arrived at 0735 and we began briefing them of the incident and what our intentions were.  We informed the fire depatment of all of the materials on the truck and there was no dangers.  IMS arrived at 0930 and began investigating the magnitude of the release and neutrilizing the area.  It was determined by VA Department of Environmental Quality that the area be neutrilized and washed down into a nearby drain.    After the intial investigation we found that a vertical crack had been made in the side of the IBC from approximately 3/4 from the top all the way to the bottom.  The IBC was strapped to the wall of the truck with a load bar in front of it.  There were no protrusions on the side of the vehicle.    We have contacted the manufacturer of the IBC to ask for assistance in determining the problem.  We are confident that we will get positive information from them, as it was clearly a container failure.  The investigation is ongoing at this time.
column169: Industrial Chemicals have taken all containers in hydrochloric acid solution out of service from that year of manufacture.

column168: Driver was making delivery to customer and discovered product leaking from a relief device on top of the storage tank.  He immediately closed the valve and shutdown the compressor, stopping the flow of product into the tank.  He then went to notify the operator just as the operator was coming out to inform him that the high level alarm had sounded.  Driver drained delivery hoses and disconnected.  Investigation into the cause of the overfill indicated that the level probe was improperly calibrated for the product and thus not reading the level in the tank correctly.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Approximately 1 gallon of product was estimated to have been released.

While off loading at the consignee the driver noticed that one of the drums was leaking. it appears that the drum had a small hole in it from a forklift accident. The driver cleaned up the spill utilizing his spill kit, repaired the hole in the drum and then had the drum overpacked. He returned the drum to the nearest Jevic facility. The duration of the release was less then one hour.
column169: Dock personnel will be instructed on how to more carefully handle freight when using automated equipment. They will also be instructed to pay particular attention to Hazardous Materials and to handle them with the appropriate care.

column168: WHILE PULLING AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA PORTABLE NURSE TRAILER WITH A PICKUP, THE TRAILER BEGAN WHIPPING FROM SIDE TO SIDE.  EMPLOYEE WAS TRAVELING ON A GRAVEL ROAD WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE WHIPPING ACTION.  THE OTHER FACTOR COULD HAVE BEEN DRIVING TOO FAST CONDITIONS.  DRIVER WAS TRAVELING 35 MPH.  WHIPPING ACTION OF TRAILER CAUSED IT TO BREAK FROM HITCH AND ROLL INTO DITCH CAUSING RELEASE.  THIS WAS A COUNTY ROAD (GRAVEL) SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE ROAD AND A DRIVEWAY LEADING TO FIELD.  AMMONIA WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH 400 GALLONS OF WATER.  THIS STOPPED THE VAPORIZATIONS PROCESS & PREVENTED ADDITIONAL VAPOR FROM LEAVING THE SITE.  WE ARE WORKING WITH A FIELDMAN FROM THE KDHE TO MAKE SURE SITE IS PROPERLY CLEANED UP.
column169: LOCATION MANAGEMENT WILL DISCUSS PROPER SPEED FOR ROAD CONDITIONS DRIVER ARE TRAVELING.  THIS WILL BE DONE IN A TOOL BOX MEETING & WILL INVOLVE ALL DRIVERS.

HE IMMEDIATELY TURNED OFF THE PUMP AND GRABBED BOOMS TO BLOCK THE SBRM SEWER & CONTAIN THE SPILL.  THE REST OF THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY & CLEANED UP BY E. G. SMITH.
column169: THE PROCEDURE FOR RECHARGING THE HOSE AFTER A PRE-SET DELIVERY WAS REVIEWED WITH THE EMPLOYEE.  THE INCIDENT WAS DOCUMENTED ON THE EMPLOYEES RECORD.  THE NOZZLE WAS INSPECTED TO SEE IF THERE WERE ANY EQUIPMENT PROBLEMS.  ALL DRIVERS HAD TO SIGN A COPY OF THE PROCEDURE.

column168: ON 3-12-05 AT APPROX 2:00 PM A CUSTOMER WAS TRANSPORTING A NURSE TANK OF NH3.  HE MET AN ONCOMING VEHICLE AT THE TOP OF A HILL AND SWERVED TO AVOID AN ACCIDENT.  THE REAR EXEL WENT IN THE DITCH CAUSING THE WHOLE NURSE TANK TO FLIP OVER.  21-CAME LOOSE FROM THE RUNNING GEAR AND ENDED UP UPSIDE DOWN IN THE DITCH.  THIS WAS ON KEIP AVE. BETWEEN 290TH & 300TH STS.  THE LIQUID VALVE CAME PARTIALLY OPEN ALLOWING LIQUID AMMONIA TO BE RELEASED INTO THE DITCH.  THIS WAS APPROX. 100 YDS FROM A SMALL CREEK.  THIS FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND COULDN'T CLOSE THE VALVE.  AGRILAND FS PEOPLE DAMMED UP THE DITCH IMMEDIATELY TO KEEP AMMONIA FROM ENETERING THE CREEK.  THE DNR WAS CALLED AT APPROX. 2:32 WHEN IT WAS DETERMINED THAT MORE THAN 100 LBS WOULD BE RELEASED.  THE FEDERAL EPA WAS NOTIFIED AT APPROX 2:45 AND WE WERE GIVEN THE NUMBER OF #752-523.  ONCE THE VALVE WAS ABLE TO BE CLOSED THE NURSE TANK WAS REMOVED FROM THE SITE.  THE DNR REPRESENTATIVE REQUESTED WE REMOVE DIRT IN THE DITCH AND WOULD INSPECT THE SITE ON THE NITH.  DIRT WAS REMOVED AND SPREAD ON A NEARBY FIELD.  IT WAS INSPECTED APPROX. 8:00 AM ON THE 14TH.  AND RELEASED AS OK.

It was a 4-compartment cargo tank.  1 compartment had nonhazardous material and was not damaged.  1 compartment was empty.  2 compartments had the hazardous material and both of them had the washout cap on the top of the trailer compromised.  About 2000 gal of product spilled out.  Local highway patrol directed traffic.  A crew from First Response was dispatched to perform corrective actions.  They were guided by the Tennessee Emergency Management Agency, the Highway Patrol and Tennessee Dept of Transportation. The locals onsite prior to First Response's arrival created a dam around the spilled product. A vacuum truck was used to clean up the spilled product.  The site was deemed clean by the local officials.
column169: Better detouring options would have prevented this accident.  This was a narrow winding road that was dangerous for trucks to be on.  Also, we are instructing our drivers to be aware of the road conditions and respond accordingly.

column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A. PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH RELEASE INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: THE BELLY OF 1269Y WAS BEING UNLOADED ON THE FLIGHT FROM BOSTON.  THE RAMP CREW NOTICED THAT SOME OF THE BOXES HAD STARTED LEAKING A YELLOW/ORANGE POWDER.  AT THIS POINT, THE RAMP SUPERVISOR ON DUTY CALLED THE DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALIST TO COME TO THE AIRCRAFT.  THE FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED INTO AN AAA CONTAINER AND MOVED INTO THE SORT BUILDING DANGEROUS GOODS AREA (EXCEPT THE THREE BOXES THAT WERE LEAKING).  THE MSDS WAS REVIEWED TO DETERMINE THE SUBSTANCE.  ALL PERSONNEL WHO CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE FREIGHT WERE INSTRUCTED TO WASH THEIR HANDS WITH SOAP AND WATER.  YELLOW ACTION TAPE WAS PLACED AROUND THE AAA CONTAINER.  THE BOXES APPEARED NOT TO BE STRONG ENOUGH TO KEEP THE INNER LINING FROM FALLING OUT OF THE BOX AND PREVENT LEAKAGE.  PHOTOS WERE TAKEN OF THE FREIGHT.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 2 CUPS OF THE POWDER THAT WAS RELEASED.
column169: IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT THE SHIPPER/OFFEROR IS TRAINED ON HOW TO PROPERLY PREPARE THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS (I.E. PAPERWORK) AND PACKAGE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: On 3/30/05, a trailer of mixed hazmat transported by Univar, USA was delivered to Onyx Environmental Services' ten day in-transit facility located in Sauget, Il.  While unloading the trailer, an Onyx employee inadvertently punctured a 55-gallon steel drum of trichloroethylene with the forklift.  The forklift was positioned under a pallet of containers which was loaded directly in front of the 55-gallon drum.  The fork of the forklift protruded out of the back side of the pallet and punctured the base of the drum, just above the bottom chime.  The puncture resulted in a 1" by 4" hole in the drum.  When the employee backed away from the drum, he noticed the drum to be leaking and immediately responded by tipping the drum on it's side to stop the release.  He exited the trailer and began containment procedures by placing oil-dry (clay) at the back of the trailer to contain the material on the trailer.  A portion of the material leaked through the floor of the trailer and out the back of the trailer where it collected in a blind sump designed specifically for spill containment.  The unloading area is a concrete decline ramp that is epoxy coated and designed to provide secondary containment for such spills.  The duration of release was approximately one minute.  The on-site spill response team at the facility was notified and clean-up began within 10 minutes of release.  The clean-up was conducted while wearing appropriate PPE and included washing the trailer floor, trailer exterior, secondary containment area and removing the accumulated liquids from clean-up activities using a vacuum truck (site owned and operated).  The 55-gallon drum was placed into an 85-gallon DM overpack container, marked and labeled in accordance with DOT requirements, and shipped to the final destination.  The manifest was annotated to identify that a spill occurred in transit and the drum was over-packed.
column169: The Onyx employee that punctured the drum was re-trained on the proper unloading techniques and use of a forklift.  A notice of the incident was posted in the unloading area, and was reviewed with other employees performing similar duties as part of a safety training meeting.

column168: After loading 26,000 lbs of THF a leak was observed from the cap on the unloading line.  The leak was secured on the unloading line by replacing the gasket in the cap.  However during that investigative and corrective action phase it was determined that the internal and external valves were not holding.  The product was immediately pumped off the trailer to the AST.  The trailer's number was 69211.
column169: Carriers must ensure that there trailers are adequate to recieve hazardous materials.  Trailers are checked for valid VINK inspection data prior to loading however it is only truely valid on the day the test was performed.  There needs to be a mechanism to determine the trailer's ability to transport hazardous materials at the time of transport.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading at the BAX Global facility in Los Angeles, California, one (1) fiberboard box was punctured by a forklift.  The fiberboard box contained one (1) 3-liter container of resin solution.  Approximately one (1) liter of free product was released and contained inside the box.  BAX Global Inc. personnel placed the entire fiberboard box into one (1) 30-gallon plastic recovery drum, along with absorbent material, to be held at the terminal pending disposal.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.  Disposal was coordinated per local, state, and federal regulations.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrences.  BAX Global Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines in relation to handling and loading of freight to all employees.

column25: DUKE POWER COMPANY - CHESTER OPERATIONS CENTER
column168: On March 9, 2005, Duke Power Company’s Chester Operations Center, located out of Chester,  South Carolina, made a hazardous waste shipment. Chester Operations Center is an EPA  Conditional Exempt Small Quantity Generator and does not have an EPA Identification Number.  This shipment was made under Manifest Document Number SCEXEMPT — 05001.  The hazardous waste shipment from the Chester Operations Center included three 55-gallon containers of hazardous waste. The hazardous waste shipment was enroute to Onyx Environmental Services, located at Creedmoor, North Carolina. Duke Power was the initial transporter of the hazardous waste. After leaving the Chester Operations Center, the DPC driver observed liquid dripping from the trailer (Trailer 9026) at 2:04 PM. He pulled off the road at exit 80, 1-85 North near Spartanburg, South Carolina. The DPC driver built a dike to contain any minor spillage until cleanup crew arrived. Approximately one gallon had leaked from the drum. Spill was reported to in-house DPC Environmental personnel at 2:24pm. Spill was cleaned-up by Duke Power Company the same day. The weather conditions during this incident were clear and cool.  Only one drum was leaking. The contents of the leaking drum were pumped into another drum. The leak originated from the bottom of the drum, but several irLches from the seam. The apparent cause of the leak was due to deterioration of the metalL bottom. Leak is believed to have started due to the drum’s bottom being deteriorated enough to start leaking after vibration while in transit. The drum was marked “UN1A2/Y1.2/100/USA/R1264/O2RL.” The content of the drum was primarily water contaminated with gasoline. The waste codes of DOOl (Ignitable), DOlO (Selenium), and D018 (Benzene) were assigned to the waste stream.
column169: The hazardous waste discharge from the metal drum was due to the drums deteriorated condition that was not discovered until the leak occurred after being vibrated during transportation. Duke Power EHS personnel, drivers, and warehouse personnel are in the process of being made aware of this DOT incident and recommendations. The emphasis to applicable Duke Power Company personnel is to not ship any drum that they question as being suitable for shipment. If a drum is in questionable condition, it is better to repackage or over-pack the drum. If a drum is exposed to weather, personnel are to make a better effort in evaluating the drum’s condition prior to usage.

The driver, after completing the fueling of construction equipment at the end of the day, did not close camlock and discharge valve properly as was not aware. He then left the area and drove for approximately one mile while the leak was occuring on a cooling canal earthen burm. The driver stated that he never relized there was a problem. Indicators show that all of the residual fuel in the system leaked out. No one knew that the leaked had occurred until the next working day when personnel arrived. Investigations on the incident immediatley began and all parties were notified. According to the findings of the investigation, the camlock and valves were not sufficiently attached and closed.
column169: The employee was terminated and a Urbieta supervisor was assigned to the site to oversee all fueling processes. All fuelers were given additional training and the specific type of fuel truck was replaced by a type that does not require camlock fitting to be moved while switching betwen different types of fuel.  The investigation concluded that on a construction site it is best management practices to have fuel trucks that have a closed valve system. One where camlocks do not need to be changed while switching from high sulfur to low sulfur fuel. Instead request trucks with the closed, valve system.

column42: AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED OR AMMONIA SOLUTIONS RELATIVE DENSITY LESS THAN .880 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: Operator discovered “B” side liquid valve leaking from packing when he opened the valve in preparation to offload rail car.  Operator closed valve, bled down hoses and connected to “A” side valve to offload car.  Operator notified corporate office.   Valve leaked minutely when closed, operator was instructed to wrap a wet towel around the valve to minimize odor while offloading car.    Car was emptied and a mobile crew dispatched to replace the “B” side valve.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Less than 5 pounds of product were estimated to have been released.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: The root cause of the incident was the loader's inattention when errantly programmed the loading meter (DEU / meter) to load 2k gallons in compt. #2, when the max capacity of the compart. was 1.5k gallons.  Contributing factors (1)Communications between the two PSC loaders during the loading, (2)PSC failed to have the driver verify data entry, (3)loading Compt. #2 without installing the skully overflow protection, (4)Incomplete loader's checklist and (5)Failure to use a separte loaders' checklist for each compartment.
column169: Corrective actions:  (1) PSC will begin filling out a complete checklist for each compart. loaded with 2nd party verifications performed by the truck driver prior to beginning loading, (2)PSC loader will only load one compartment at a time and verify the skully is in the compartment that is loading prior to start, (3)PSC will fully engage the truck drivers to perform the required 2nd party verification checks per the loaders' checklist, (4)PSC held a procedure stand down communicating to all PSC loaders that Normal procedures must be followed while performing any work activity, (6) Communications must be maintained between loaders, PSC loaders will not share responsibilities loading a truck, except for verification requirements prior to the start of the loading process, (6)PSC instructed each loader that signing off the loader's checklist after the checks have been made is the responsibility of the PSC loader loading the conveyance.

column42: BUTANE SEE ALSO PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED
column168: Upon initiating the transfer of butane a leak of butane was observed between the snappy-joe connection and the rail car.  The transfer was terminated and upon examination the liquid unloading valve on the rail car had a bad gasket.  The car was side tracked and the customer sent in a third party repair company to replace the gasket.  The gasket was replaced and the rail car was off loaded without further incident.  Butane that escaped immediately disippated.

column168: INTERMODAL CRANE OPERATOR PLACED ISO TANK CONTAINER ICSU 28156 INTO THE BOTTOM WELL OF AN INTERMODAL RAIL FLATCAR AT 1416 HRS. CST ON 3/07/05.  THE TRACK WITH RAIL FLATCAR WITH ICSU 28156 ABOARD WAS RELEASED AT 1526 HRS. CST TO BE REPOSITIONED IN RAILYARD FOR TRAIN MAKEUP.  AT 1630 HRS. CST, A BNSF SWITCH CREW NOTICED A WHITE SMOKE (VAPOR CLOUD) EMANATING FROM ICSU 28156.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAIL FLATCAR WITH ICSU 28156 WAS CORDONED OFF.  BNSF AND CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET EXTENSION WITH CAP (THAT EXTENDED APPROX. 2 1/2 INCHES BEYOND THE ISO TANKS METAL FRAME) WAS DAMAGED AND LEAKING PRODUCT.  APPARENTLY, THIS VALVE'S CAP WAS DAMAGED WHEN BEING PLACED INTO THE WELL OF THE INTERMODAL FLATCAR.  THIS VALVE (EXTENDING BEYOND THE PROTECTION OF THE OUTER METAL FRAME) STRUCK THE SIDEWALL OF THE RAILCAR WELL DURING LOADING OPERATIOSN AND THIS DAMAGE WENT UNOTICED.  ICSU 28156 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A TANKER TRUCK AND RETURNED TO THE BENEFICIAL SHIPPER AT FREEPORT, TX.  ICSU 28156 WAS WATER WASHED AFTERWARDS.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WITH EXTENSIONS WAS REMOVED AND THE ORIFICE BLIND FLANGED.  ICSU 28156 WAS EARMARKED TO BE TRANSPORTED TO REPAIR FACILITY.  BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS APPLIED ABSORBANT AND NEUTRALIZER TO THE SPILLAGE AREA AT THE BALLAST AND GROUND IMPACT LOCATIONS.  LATER, THE NEUTRALIZER WAS VACUUMED AND ALL VACUUMED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO DISPOSAL DRUMS FOR APPROPRIATE DISPOSAL.  THE SPILLAGE INSIDE THE RAIL FLATCAR WELL WAS WIPED AND CLEANED.  ALTHOUGH THE LOCAL F.D. WAS ON SCENE THEY HAD MINIMAL INVOLVEMENT IN THIS INCIDENT.
column169: LOADER OF PRODUCT INTO ISO TANK NEEDED TO REMOVE OUTLET VALVE EXTENSIONS PRIOR TO SHIPMENT OR ENSURE THAT THEY DID NOT EXTEND BEYOND THE PROTECTIVE METAL FRAME STRUCTURE.

column168: LIQUID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM TRAILER 313-6928 AT THE ENTRANCE GATE TO THE RENO, NV (URE) SERVICE CENTER.  TRAILER WAS DRIVEN TO THE REAR OF THE YARD.  A DAM OF ABSORBANT WAS BUILT AROUND THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND THE REAR DOOR WAS OPENED.  A 55 GALLON DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE A 2 INCH PUNCTURE ABOUT 8 INCHES FROM THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THE CAUSE OF THE PUNCTURE WAS FREIGHT THAT HAD FALLEN FROM A LOAD RACK IMMEDIATELY TO THE REAR OF THE DRUMS, AND A PIECE OF THE PRODUCT HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH THE METAL DRUM, CAUSING THE PUNCTURE.  UNIVERSAL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF THE SPILL.
column169: A LETTER OF INSTRUCTION WILL BE ISSUED TO THE DRIVER WHO FAILED TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE THE CYLINDER THAT FELL AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  THE PERSON WILL BE COUNSELED ABOUT THE ERROR AND RE-TRAINED IF NECESSARY.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE DRIVER DIVERTED FROM HIS DELIVERY ROUTE IN ORDER TO FUEL HIS TRUCK.  WHEN MAKING A U-TURN TO ENTER THE PROPER DRIVEWAY HIS TRAILER ROLLED OVER.  THE TRAILER DID NOT RUPTURE FROM THE ACCIDENT AND NO PRODUCT ESCAPED.  ALL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED (FIRE, HAZ MAT RESPONDERS, OES AND OUR EMERGENCY SPILL RECOVERY TEAM) AND ALL RESPONDED.  IN ORDER TO UPRIGHT THE TRAILER THE CARGO HAD TO BE MOVED TO ANOTHER TRUCK.  TO ACCOMPLISH THIS TASK, IT IS NECESSARY TO DRILL A 4" HOLE IN EACH COMPARTMENT (20) CONTAINING CARGO, INSERT A SUNCTION TUBE AND SUCK THE CARGO OUT.  DOUBLE BULKHEADS SEPARATE EACH COMPARTMENT.  WHEN WE DRILLED THE FIRST HOLE THE VACUUM CONTAINED IN THAT COMPARTMENT WAS RELEASED, AND PRODUCT FLOWED THRU A CRACK IN ITS INTERIOR BULKHEAD INTO THE ANNULAR SPACE AND OUT THE INSPECTION BUNG IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ORDERED ALL PERSONNEL BEHIND THE DESIGNATED SAFETY LINE UNTIL THE FLOW STOPPED.  AFTERWARDS WE CONTINUED WITH THE RECOVERY PROCEDURE AND UP RIGHTED THE TRAILER.  A WASTE DISPOSAL SERVICE WAS ON SIGHT, THEY VACUUMED THE PRODUCT FROM THE STREET AND STORM DRAINS AS WELL AS JETTING ALL STORM DRAINS AND RECOVERING THAT MATERIAL AS WELL.  THE HEALTH DEPARTMENT RELEASED ALL RESWPONDERS AT 05:00HRS, THEY DECLARED THE AREA SAFE AND CLEAN.
column169: A DETAILED ANALYSIS THAT ADDRESSES THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WILL BE SHARED WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS THRU SAFETY BULLETINS, TAILGATE METTINGS AND DURING OUR NEXT ROUND OF SAFETY MEETINGS.  ALSO A PROCEDURE CHANGE HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED FOR CARGO RECOVERY.  IF AN EVENT SHOULD HAPPEN AGAIN, ALL BUNGS WILL BE PLUGGED PRIOR TO ANY DRILLING AND UP RIGHTING OPERATIONS.

column168: ON MARCH 13, 2005 AT 6:15 PM CENTRAL STANDARD TIME THE DRIVER OF THE WERNER ENTERPRISES TRACTOR-TRAILER DISCOVERED A SPILL IN THE TRAILER.  A PALLET OF MATERIAL HAD FALLEN OVER IN THE TAIL OF THE TRAILER AND APPROXIMATELY 6 GALLONS OF AQUATUFF HAD LEAKED OUT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED FOR A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO CLEAN UP THE LEAK.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND QUICKLY ABSORBED THE SPILL WITH RAGS AND GRANULAR ABSORBENTS.  THE LEAKING CONTAINERS WERE CLEANED AND RE-SEALED.  THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS WASHED DOWN WITH A MILD ACIDIC SOAP AND WATER TO NEUTRALIZE ALL RINSEATE.  THE RAGS AND ABSORBENTS WERE PACKAGED AND SENT OFF FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE ENTIRE INCIDENT FROM DISCOVERY TO CLEAN UP LASTED APPROXIMATELY 7 HOURS.
column169: AFTER INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT, IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE SCREW CAPS ON THE 5 GALLON CONTAINERS WERE DEFECTIVE.  THEY WERE NOT BROKEN OR DAMAGED FROM THE FALL, YET THEY STILL LEAKED WHEN NOT HELD PERFECTLY UPRIGHT.  TO PREVENT ANY RECURRENCE WE WILL BE SPEAKING TO THE SHIPPER ABOUT THE CONTAINERS AND THE POTENTIAL FOR IMPROVEMENTS.  IN ADDITION WE WILL BE REVIEWING BLOCKING AND BRACING FOR PALLETS TO PREVENT ANY FALL OF MATERIAL AT ALL.

OUR DRIVER HAD STOPPED AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 45 & HWY 92 WHEN HE PROCEEDED TO TURN LEFT THE TANK SURGED FORWARD AND OVERTURNED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN THE VALVES ON THE TANK CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE SOFT GROUND CAUSING THE VALVE HAND WHEELS TO TURN AND CAUSING VALVE STEM DAMAGE.  THE ROLLCAGE PROTECTION WORKED WELL ON SOLID GROUND BUT WHEN THE ROLLCAGE ENTERED INTO SOFT GROUND IT ALLOWED CONTACT WITH THE VALVES.  THE LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICES RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND USED WATER SPRAY TO CONTROL VAPOR RELEASE UNTIL THE LIQUID VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE VAPOR VALVE WAS CAPPED STOPPING THE RELEASE.
column169: THE HORIZONTAL BARS ON THE ROLLCAGE ARE LOCATED TO CLOSE TO THE TANK SURFACE AND SHOULD BE LOCATED FURTHER UP THE FRAME.

column168: Tank car arrived at supplier for loading.  Upon starting to load, a leak was discovered at the sample port.  A mobile crew was dispatched to affect a repair.  Mobile repair crew put in a self-tapping bolt and put putty around the bolt to seal it.  Car was then depressurized, leak tested and released to the shop.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Car was empty prior to supplier beginning to load it, so a minute amount of material was released, likely less than one (1) pound.

While preparing the railcar for unloading, driver discovered that the “A” side valve was minutely leaking through when he removed the plug from the valve.  He checked that valve was closed to try and stop leak.  Unable to do so, he replaced the plug in the valve and contacted the corporate office.  Driver was instructed to unload from “B” side valve and to monitor the “A” side valve.  No material was found to be leaking from the “A” side valve at this time.  He tagged the valve “do not use”.  Once rail car is emptied, it will be depressurized and a mobile repair crew brought in to affect a repair.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Approximately 2.5 pounds of product (vapor) was estimated to have been released.    NOTE:  Supplemental submission was to correct the amount released.  The printout received showed 1 pound instead of 3, as indicated in the above description.

column168: Driver was making delivery to customer when the fitting on the vapor hose disconnected, releasing vapor from the delivery hose.  Driver donned appropriate protective equipment and closed the isolation valve on the vapor line, stopping the release.  Driver then reconnected the fitting, ensured it was tight, and completed the delivery.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Approximately 5 pounds of vapor was estimated to have been released.      NOTE:  Material was released in vapor form, however, this system requires the units released to match the physical state of the material, so its listed in question #19 as liquid pounds, not gas.

Driver making delivery of 12% sodium hypochlorite to remote village water treatment building.  Three small "tanks" in building, none had identification.  Driver put six gallons of hypochlorite in the wrong tank, which had 17 gallons of 6% ammonia in it, he noticed odor, discontinued unload process.  Driver leaving tank to stow hose when mixture in tank of 6 gallons of 12% sodium hypochlorite with 17 gallons of 6% ammonia "exploded"/burst the tank.  Driver was not injured.  No product contacted him.  6 pounds of chlorine dispersed from mixture of ammonia with hypochlorite.  Spilled liquid was minimal and did not contact drain, did not contact the environment or leave floor of building, evaporated before cleanup occurred.

column168: THE TRANSPORTATION UNIT WAS A FLAT BED TRAILER BELONGING TO UNIVAR INC. WITH A 1000 GAL MC-312 AS TANK MOUNTED ON THE TRAILER.  ALL FITTINGS AND HOSES ALSO BELONG TO UNIVAR INC.  THE TRAILER WAS PICKED UP BY A DRIVER FROM B.J. CECIL TRUCKING, INC. AND TRANSPORTED TO CONTENCE TO ITS DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING.  THE UNLOADING IS DONE THROUGH A FENCE TO APS'S FACILITY.  THE HOSES AND COUPLINGS WERE CONNECTED TOGETHER BY APS'S EMPLOYEES ON THERE SIDE OF THE FENCE AND BY THE DRIVER TO THE TANK ON THE FLAT BED TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS TOLD BY APS EMPLOYEES THAT ALL WAS HOOKED UP AND TO START THE FLOW OF PRODUCT.  WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE VALVES ON THE TANK THE FITTINGS BEGAN TO LEAK SO THE DRIVER SHUT THE VALVES OFF TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT AND AT THE SAME TIME THE APS'S EMPLOYEES YELLED TO THE DRIVER TO SHUT THE VALVES AS THE CONNECTIONS WERE ALL LEAKING.  APS EMPLOYEES WALKED THE HOSES TO IN OUT THE PRODUCT AND PASSED THE HOSES BACK THRU THE FENCE TO THE DRIVER TO LOAD BACK ON THE TRAILER.  SOME RESIDUAL PRODUCT WAS LEFT IN THE HOSES AND SOME WAS ON THE FLAT BED.  THE DRIVER WAS TO LEAVE THE PROPERTY AND TAKE THE LOAD BACK TO UNIVAR.  THE DRIVER RETURNED THE TRAILER TO UNIVAR AS DIRECTED AND IN TRANSIT CAUSTIC SODA SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY FROM THE FLAT BED TRAILER AND HOSES.
column169: HOSES AND COUPLINGS SHOULD BE MAINTAINED TO KEEP THEM FROM LEAKING.

column168: ON FEBRUARY 15, 2005 A SHIPMENT WAS MADE FROM NORTH ANNA POWER STATION TO TRIJICON, INC. FOR THE REPAIR OF THREE REFLEX SIGHT RIFLE SCOPES. THE RIFLE SCOPES CONTAIN TTITIUM GAS. THE PACKAGE WAS SHIPPED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 173.422 AS AN EXCEPTED PACKAGE FOR RADIOACTIVE INSTRUMNTS AND ARTICLES. THE ADDITIONAL REQUIREMTNS FOR EXCEPTED PACKAGES CONTAINED IN 49 CFR 173.422 (A) WERE FOLLOWED WHEREBY THE UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBERS WAS PLACED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE. FOLLOWING REPAIRS TRIJICON, INC. SHIPPED THE REFLEX SIGHT RIFLE SCOPES BACK TO NORTH ANNA. ON MARCH 28, 2005 NORTH ANNA WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL NOTIFIED THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL / RADWASTE SHIPPING OFFICE THAT A PACKAGE HAD ARRIVED FROM TRIJICON, INC. OF WIXOM, MICHIGAN. TECHNICIANS WERE DISPATCHED TO RECEIPT INSPECT AND SURVEY THE PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION IT WAS NOTED THAT THE UN IDENTIFICATION NUMBERS ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE PACKAGE WERE COVERED BY TAPE MAKING THE NUMBER ILLEIGIBLE. STATION RADIOLOGICAL PROTECTION SUPERVISION AND TRIJICON, INC. WERE NOTIFIED OF AN APPARENT VIOLATION OF 49 CFR 17..422 (A). THIS EVEN WAS DTERMINED TO REPORTABLE IN ACCORDANCE WITH 49 CFR 171.16 (A)(4) FOR DISCOVERY OF AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.     THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF THE PACKAGE AND NO RELEASE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THIS EVENT. INITIAL SURVEYS PERFORMED BY STATION TECHNICIANS NOTED NOT CONTAMINATION.
column169: IT IS RECOMMENDED THAT TRIJICON, INC. MAKE CHANGES AS NECESSARY TO ENSURE INDIVIDUALS ENGAGED IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS ARE PROPERLY TRAINED TO PRECLUDE RECURRENCE.

column168: ROYSTER-CLARK ASSOCIATE WAS TOWING AMMONIA NURSE WAGON WESTBOUND ON KY HWY 94.  THE WAGON STARTED TO WHIP BACK AND FORTH AND THE TRUCK AND WAGON DROPPED OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  THE OPERATOR LOST CONTROL AND CROSSED TO THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND CAME TO REST IN A FIELD OWNED BY REX GILBERT OF LYNVILLE, KY.  THE WAGON SAPARATED FROM THE TRUCK AND ROLLED OVER INTO THE RIGHT SIDE DITCH.  THE WITHDRAWAL VALVE AND THE RELIEF VALVE WERE BOTH DAMAGED, ALLOWING THE AMMONIA TO ESCAPE.  IN 15 TO 20 MINUTES, WHEN THE AMMONIA DROPPED BELOW THE WITHDRAWAL TUBE, THE TANK DEPRESSURIZED AND ROYSTER-CLARK ASSOCIATES WERE ABLE TO STABILIZE THE TANK, CHANGE THE DAMAGED WITHDRAWAL VALVE AND PLUG THE RELIEF VALVE.  THE REMAINING AMMONIA WAS TRANSFERRED TO AN EMPTY NURSE WAGON.  THE CUBA KENTUCKY FIRE DEPT. AND THE KY STATE POLICE RESPONDED.  NO WATER WAS USED TO CONTROL THE SPILL.  THE STATE POLICE DIRECTED TRAFFIC AROUND THE TANK, BUT THE ROAD WAS NEVER SHUT DOWN.  NO OTHER VEHICLES WERE INVOLVED.  MR. GILBERT'S PROPERTY WILL BE MONITORED, BUT NO DAMAGE IS EXPECTED.
column169: ALL ASSOCIATES WILL BE RETRAINED AND INSTRUCTED ON PROPER AMMONIA NURSE WAGON TOWING PROCEDURES.

column168: A RETIRED FORMER BNSF EMPLOYEE REPORTED ENTRAINED RCRX 1050 PARKED IN RAIL SLIDING AT DES MOINES, NM LEAKING PRODUCT FROM ONE OF THE TOP FITTINGS.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS REPORTED LIQUID PRODECT ON THE SIDES AND TOP OF RCRX 1050 WITH NO PRODUCT IMPACTING THE GROUND.  RESPONDERS FOUND TOW OF THREE SECUREMENT BOLTS WITH NUTS ON THE VAPORT VALVE FLANGE FITTING ATOP A RUBBER SURGE BAFFLE LOOSE.  THIS LOOSE SECUREMENT ALLOWED THE HORIZONTAL VALVE TO LEAN DOWNWARD FROM THE RUBBER BAFFLE WHICH CREATED AN ONE INCH GAP AT THE FLANGE AREA FOR THE PRODUCT TO ESCAPE DURING TRAIN MOVEMENT.  THE LOOSE SECUREMENT NUTS TO THE BOLTS WERE TOOL TIGHTENED.  RESPONDERS ALSO CHECKED THE SEUCUREMENT ON THE OTHER TOP FITTINGS FINDING OTHER BOLTS LOOSE BUT NO PRODUCT LEAKS FROM THESE FITTINGS.  THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS FOUND INTACT.  SPILLAGE NEUTRALIZED AND WASHED WITH A SOLUTION OF BAKING SODE AND WATER, THEN WIPED AFTER A FRESH WATER RINSE APPLIED.  NO FURTHER LEAKAGE NOTED AFTER SECUREMENT AND SPILL REMEDIATION COMPLETED BY 1510 H RS. MST, 3/22/05

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS ENTERING A LEFT HAND CORNER WHEN HE RECOGNIZED THAT HE WAS APPROACHING TO FAST.  THE DRIVER TAPPED HIS BRAKES AND THE LIQUID IN THE TANK USED THE NATURAL ENERTIA FORCE TO CAUSE THE TRAILER TO START TO TIP OVER.  THE DRIVER THEN AGAIN HIT HIS BRAKES HOPING TO SLOW THE VEHICLE ENOUGH FOR THE TRAILER TO STOP LEANING AND RIGHT ITSELF.  THE ATTEMPT FAILED AND THE FORCE OF THE TRAILER LEANING CAUSED THE TRACTOR TO ROLL-OVER AND SKID OFF THE HIGHWAY INTO THE ROCKY AND GRASSY DITCH.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF ANY PRODUCT.  THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO OTHER UNITS AND THE WRECKED VEHICLE WAS TOWED TO A STORAGE YARD.
column169: DRIVER WAS TERMINATED DUE TO HIS ACTIONS.  THE INCIDENT WAS SHARED WITH THE TRANSPORTATION FLEET ABOUT RECOGNIZING THE IMPACT OF SPEED IN RELATION TO THE ENERTIA FORCE WHEN CARRYING A LIQUID PRODUCT.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS SENT FROM THE MILWAUKEE, WI TERMINAL TO THE SCHAUMBURG, IL TERMINAL.  THE CYLINDERS WERE TENDERED TO WATKINS ON SKIDS.  SOME WERE SITTING UPRIGHT AND SOME ON THEIR SIDES.  ALL CYLINDERS WERE ON PALLETS AND BANDED AND THE LOAD WAS BLOCKED WITH LOGISTICS STICKS, MTY PALLETS AND AIRBAGS.  IN TRANSIT THE 800 TO 1000 LB TANKS BROKE THROUGH THE PALLETS AND TOPPLED OVER INTO ONE ANOTHER CAUSING A VALVE TO CRACK AND BEGIN SLOWLY LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL IN SCHAUMBURG THE TRAILER WAS OPENED.  WHEN THE CHECKER SAW THE TANKS LYING THROUGHOUT THE TRAILER HE GOT A CAMERA TO DOCUMENT THE DAMAGE.  UPON RETURNING TO THE TRAILER HE ENTERED TO TAKE PICTURES AND FELT LIGHT HEADED AS HE DISCOVERED A TANK LEAKING BY A HISSING SOUND.  THE CHECKER ALERTED THE OPERATIONS MGR. AND TERMINAL MGR.  THE DOOR WAS CLOSED IMMEDIATELY AND THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO THE YARD.  MSDS WAS RETRIEVED AND EMI CONTACTED FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  TWO EMPLOYEES WENT TO THE CLINIC FOR OBSERVATION ONLY AND WERE NOT TREATED.  ONE EMPLOYEE REFUSED TREATMENT SAYING HE FELT NO REACTION.  A TOTAL OF THREE EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED.  NO LOST WORK DAYS.  NO INJURY OR ILLNESS.
column169: THE LOAD SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN PICKED UP FROM THE SHIPPER.  THE CYLINDERS WERE FAR TOO HEAVY FOR THE PALLETS THEY WERE LOADED ONTO.  ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED RECEIVED SAFETY REVIEWS.

column168: AT 1020 HOURS ON MARCH 19TH TANK CAR ACFX78993 WAS REPORTED LEAKING PRODUCT IN CSX TRANPORTATION'S AUGUST YARD.  CSX MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMETED THE CORPORTATIONS TRANSPORTATION EMERGECY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAIL CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER / CONSIGNEE, DSM CHEMICALS WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  DSM REPRESENTATIVES SECURED THE RELEASE AND THE CAR WAS FORWARDED TO THEIR FACILITY LOCATED JUST OUTSIDE THE AUGUSTA YARD TEMINAL.  APPROXIMATELY SEVENTY-FIVE (75) GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  THE PRODUCT SOLIDIFIED AND WAS PICKED UP BY DSM REPRESENTATIVES AND REMOVED FROM THE PROPERTY. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT IS BELIEVED THE RAIL CAR HAS A CRACKED SHELL.    NARRI   2(5+3) X (3+0) = 48

WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SELKIRK, NY, A FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTARTION INSPECTOR DISCOVERED THAT TANK CAR GATX79679, RESIDUE, ALCOHOLS, NOS, WAS HISSING.  CSXT'S MECHANICAL FOREMAN INSPECTED THE CAR AND REPORTED THAT THE HISSING WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY COVER NEAR THE HINGE.  HE FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT NEXT TO THE HINGE WAS NOT HAND TIGHT AND WAS ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE.  HE TIGHTENED THE BOLT WRENCH TIGHT AND CHECKED ALL THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS TO ENSURE THEY WERE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE HISSING STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER, AVENTINE RENEWABLE ENERGY, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND THEY WERE ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE.    NARRI: 5(4+3)X(2+0) = 70

column168: A CITIZEN IN HAYDEN, AL REPORTED TO CSX TRANSPORTATION'S PLICE COMMUNICATION CENTER THAT HE OBSERVED A TANK CAR IN A PASSING TRAIN TO BE LEAKING A WHITE SUBSTANCE THAT APPEARED TO SOLIDIFY ON TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CHIEF DISPATCHER FOR THE TERRITORY WAS NOTIFIED AND HE IDENTIFIED THE TRAIN THAT JUST PASSED THROUGH HAYDEN AS THE Q57814.  A ROLL BY INSPECTION OF THE TRAIN REVEALED THAT A TANK CAR, UTLX 910730, REISUDE PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED, HAD ICE BUILD UP ON THE PROTECTIVE DOME. CSXT  S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO MEET THE TRAIN AND TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AT CSXT'S DECATUR, AL RAILY YARD.  THEY FOUND THAT THE "B" END LIQUID VALVE WAS OPEN ABOUT 1/8TH TURN AND VALVE PLUG WAS NOT INSTALLED.  THE CONTRACTOR CLOSED THE VALVE AND INSTALLED THE VALVE PLUG.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.  THE SHIPPER, MARATHON ASHLAND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

column168: TRAIN INFORMATION  Y101/20 38 X 2 = 4,206 TONS, 2,443 FEET  FRONTIER YARD WEST END PULLDOWN CREW ON DUTY AT 0659.  CONDITIONS  TIME:0830  TEMP. 35 DEGREES  PRECIP. LIGHT DRIZZLE  WINDS: NORTH WEST 5-7 MPH    INCIDENT DESCRIPTION  Y101 CREW WAS INSTRUCTED FROM THE WEST END YARDMASTER TO DOUBLE UP TRACKS 53 & 56 AND PULL THEM UP TO BAILEY AVE.  AFTER RECEIVING A BLOCKING DEVICE ON BOTH TRACKS THE CREW TIED ONTO CLASS 53.  THE CONDUCTOR TIED AIR INTO SIX CARS AND PROCEEDED TO PULL THE TRACK UP THE LADDED TO SEVEN LEAD TO DOUBLE TO CLASS 56.  THE CREW PULLED OFF CLASS 53 WITH A 2464-1007 MOTHER SLUG SET WITH 38X2=4,206TONS. WHILE PULLING OUT THE LEAD THE CONDUCTOR NOTICED THAT THE CARS BEGAN TO DERAIL AND TOLD HIS ENGINEER TO STOP HIS TRAIN.  THE ENGINEER IMEEDIATELY PLACED HIS TRAIN INTO EMERGENCY.  UPON INPECTION BY THE CONDUCTOR IT WAS FOUND THAT THE 27TH THROUGH 30TH CARS WERE DERAILED.  THE TIRED CAR IN THIS INCIDENT WAS THE PROX 46085, WHICH WAS LOADED DANGEROUS TANK OF PROPYLENE TETRAMER.  IT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.    UPON CHECKING WITH THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK, THE TRAINMASTER ON DUTY DECIDED TO EVACUATE EMPLOYEES TO AT LEAST 1000 FT FROM THE SCENE.  THIS EVACUATED THE SHOP AREA AS WELL AS THE DIESEL HOUSE FACILITY.  ALL YARD CREWS WITHIN THIS AREA WERE ALSO EVACUATED TO THE WEST END YARD OFFICE TO AWAIT FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS.  ALL THE LOCOMOTIVES IN THIS AREA WERE SHUT DOWN BECAUSE OF POSSIBLE IGNITION SOURCES.    HAZARDOUS INFORMATION  THE RAIL CAR INVOLVED WAS THE PROX 46085.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE WAS SHEERED OFF FROM THE DERAILMENT.  THE 90-DEGREE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS ALSO DAMAGED AND WAS THE PRIMARY SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  INITIALLY THE CAR WAS LEAKING AT A ARATE OF 4 TO 5 GALLONS A MINUTE.  THIS TANK CAR WAS PATCHED AND CONTAINED AT @ 1130 HOURS BY THE HAZMAT TEAM.    CAUSE:  T221 - BROKEN RAIL - VERTICAL SPLIT HEAD  ATARI: 5(5+1+0)(4+0)=120

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S CONDUCTOR REPORTED THAT TANK CAR, TGAX131014, LOAD PHOSPHORIC ACID, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK AS THEY WERE SWITCHING THE CAR ONTO THE SIDING AT COTTAGE GROVE, IN.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  THE INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER, PCS SALES, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AND COMPANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGERS TO THE SCENE.  IN THE MEAN TIME, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AT SCXT'S REQUEST, OBTAINED A PLASTIC WATERING TROUGH FROM A NEARBY FARM SUPPLY STORE AND PLACED IT UNDER THE TANK CAR TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  AN EMPTY TANK, UTLX 12346, WAS OBTAINED FROM THE CONSIGNEE AND THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED FROM THE LEAKING CAR.  THE SPILL AREA ON THE MAINLINE TRACK WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.  THE AREA WHERE THE LEAKING CAR WAS SITTING WAS ALSO NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND THE TRACK WAS REMOVED SO THAT THE IMPACTED WOILS AND BALLAST COULD BE EXCAVATED.  THE LOADED CAR, UTLX 12346 WILL BE FORWARDED TO ROYSTER CLARK AT KITCHELL, IN AND PCS SALES IS OBTAINING AN FRA APPROVAL TO MOVE THE PREVIOUSLY LEAKING CAR TO A RAIL CAR REPAIR FACILITY.

THIS CAR WAS ENROUTE TO A TANK CAR SHOP FOR REPAIRS TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT THE TIME OF THIS INCIDENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL NOTED DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS MATERIAL WHICH HAD LEAKED INTO THE LAYER BETWEEN THE TANK SHELL AND JACKET AND WAS DRIPPING AFTER THE CAR HAD BEEN PULLED FROM THE SHIPPER'S PLANT.    THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO THE PLANT FOR FURTHER REPAIRS, CLEANING AND PURGING BEFORE BIENG FORWARDED FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REAPIARS.

A BNSF SWITCHING MISHAP WAS REPORTED IN CLOVIS, NM RAILYARD WITH THE INITIAL REPORT INDICATING THAT NO TRANSPORTED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE INVOLVED.  THIS SWITCHING MISHAP WAS THE RESULT OF A SHOVING MOVEMENT WITH NO PERSON AT THE LEADING END OF THE MOVEMENT.  TWO INTERMODAL FLATCARS COLLIDED BUT DID NOT DERAIL, ALTHOUGH A CONTAINER (MSCU 383815) ATOP ONE OF THE FLATCARS INVOLVED WAS DAMAGED DURING THE COLLISION.  MSCU 383815, WHICH WAS BILLED FAK, SUSTAINED A CUT/TEAR INTO THE CONTAINER SIDEWALL.  AT THE START OF THE LADING TRANSFER OF MSCU 383815 IT WAS REPORTED THAT IT CONTAINED 80 DRUMS OF UN1197, FLAVORING LIQUID EXTRACT, A CLASS 3.  THE BILLING WAS CORRECTED TO PROPERLY INDICATE THIS HAZARDOUS SHIPMENT.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS REPORTED FIVE 55 GALLON STEEL DRUMS INSIDE MSCU 383815 WERE CUT NEAR THE DRUM BOTTOMS WHICH CORRESPONDED TO THE CUT IN THE CONTAINER SIDEWALL FROM THE COLLISION.  UNDAMAGED DRUMS WERE TRANSFERRED TO AN INTERMODAL TRAILER FOR FURTHERANCE TO DESTINATION.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS, WHICH LOST THEIR ENTIRE CONTENTS, REMAINED INSIDE MSCU 383815 FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS REMEDIATED.

column168: SHIPMENT WAS SITTING ON THE DOCK, THE BOXES LOOSE ON A PALLET. column168: ON APRIL 6, 2005, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM EXPERIENCED A COMPROMISED DRUM.  AS A RESULT APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE WAS RELEASED INTO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND BELOW.  AT APPROXIMATELY 8:04 PM CDT, KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES CONTACTED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE AND BASED ON THE CONVERSION DISPATCHED A CREW FROM BELLON ENVIRONMENTAL TO PERFORM THE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CREW FROM BELLON ARRIVED ON-SITE TO ASSESS THE SCOPE OF THE RELEASE.  THE MATERIAL HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM THE NOSE AND REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THEY INVESTIGATED THE SOURCE AND FOUND THAT A NAIL THAT HAD COME LOSE FROM THE PALLET RUPTURED THE DAMAGED DRUM.  THE CREW BEGAN CLEAN UP PROCEDURE THEY NEUTRALIZED THE MATERIAL WITH VINEGAR AND WATER SOLUTION, AND CLEARED THE FLOORING OF THE TRAILER AND THE GROUND BELOW.  THE ABSORBENTS WERE USED AS PADDING FOR THE DRUM IN THE OVER PACK CONTAINER.  THE RUPTURED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO THE OVER PACK AND RE-PACKED ONTO THE TRAILER FOR SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ON MARCH, 12, 2005 A KLLM EMPLOYEE NOTICED A SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF A TRAILER DURING ROUTINE INSPECTIONS.  ON MARCH 12, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM, KLLM RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  BASED ON AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM TAS ENVIRONMENTAL (TAS) TO ASSESS THE SITE AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CREW FROM TAS ARRIVED ON-SITE AND ENTERED THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, TAS PERSONNEL OBSERVED ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM LEAKING ADHESIVE, NEAR THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  THE CREW UTILIZED A FORK TRUCK AND A PALLET JACK TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER.  THE FREE-STANDING ADHESIVE WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND PLACED INTO A 30-GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS OVER PACKED INTO AN 85-GALLON POLY OVERPACK AND STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.

It seems the shipper Put a drum into on overpack drum that had a crack in the bottom.  Before placing the drum in the overpack, they placed styrofoam in the bottom.  The drum was loaded on a pallet, with 4 others.  The pallet was loaded toward the nose of the trailer and then other drums were double stacked, between the rear and the nose of the trailer, preventing the driver from seeing the front items.  The manifest listed the suspect items as "Empty, last residue contained...".    Driver's Report:                                                        AT 3:30 PM I PULLED INTO THE PETRO AT   EXIT 848 IN BAEUMONT TX PULLING         TRAILER 1358, I INSPECTED THE OUTSIDE   OF THE UNIT (201 AND 1358) NOT FINDING  FAULT, I ENTERED RESTRAUNT AND EAT      DINNER, I RETURNED 45 MINUTES LATER TO  DO A WALK AROUND, THUS AGAIN FINDING    NO FAULT, AROUND 2 HRS LATER I HEARD    TALKING AROUND MY UNIT INVESTAGATING I  FOUND PUDDLE OF WATERY SUBSTANCE UNDER  MY TRAILER, ON FURTHER INVESTAGAION I   NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A DRIP COMMING   FROM THE MIDDLE (AROUND TURN LAMP) OF   THE TRAILER, I PUT ON GLOVES AND        ENTERED THE TRAILER AND FOUND LIQUID    ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AS WELL AS ON THE  DRUMS. I RETURNED TO THE CAB OF MY      TRUCK AND NOTIFIED TRAY, HE CALLED      CLEAN HARBORS, H. WEBSTER ARIVED        AROUND 30 MINS LATER, UPON              INVESTAGATING HE CALLED OUT A           CLEANUP/INVESTAGATION TEAM.             WHEN THEY ARRIVED ME, H. WEBSTER AND    O. PINDER ENTERED THE TRAILER, FINDING  AN OVER PAC CONTAINER WITH A CRACK IN   2 INCHES IN DIAMATER IN THE BOTTOM OF   CONTAINER, AFTER FURTHER LOOKING, THE   CRACK HAD STIRAFOME INSERTED TO STOP    LEAKING.. THE DRUM INSIDE WAS UPSIDE    DOWN. H. WEBSTER STATED THAT I WAS NOT  AT FAULT, BUT THE PARTY TO WHOME        PACKED THE OVER PAC WAS AT FAULT FOR    USING A FAULTY CONTAINMENT CONTAINER.   W. SMITH AND C. WEBSTER REMAINED OUT    SIDE AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL OUT SIDE  THE TRAILER, USING 1 BAG OF SORBANT     SWEEP, WHILE WE USED 3 BAGS INSIDE THE  TRAILER... 9:30PM THE SPILL WAS         CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP, THE TRAILER   STILL NEEDS TO BE CONTAINED AND CLEAN,  CLEAN HARBOR'S REP H. WEBSTER STATED    THAT DEAR PARK WILL CLEAN 1358 ONCE     THEY HAVE OFFLOADED THE UNIT...         THE SUBSTANCE,  IN THE OVERPAC WAS        CLASS 8, UN2922

The driver for CTL Distribution started the unloading process at the Rhodia unloading pit when it was determined that the product was not flowing through the customers line. The driver for CTL contact a plant operator and the plant operator determined that the prior driver from another carrier had not properly drained the plants unloading hose prior to closing the valve to the plant's unloading pit. Sulfur backed up into the unloading hose to the discharge valve on the trailer causing the sulfur to harden in the line. The driver had problems getting the discharge valve closed and it took several attempts to get the valve completely closed. Bill James the plant operator for Rhodia verified that it was Rhodia equipment that failed causing the product spill. Rhodia plant personnel performed the required clean up.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS LOREN LORENZO AND THOMAS CASPER DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A PLASTIC LAB PACK WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE LAB PACK FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS LAB PACK TO CONTAIN SEVEN PLASTIC SPECIMEN CUPS.  THE CLOSURE ON ONE CUP WAS LOOSE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 1 OZ OF ITS CONTENTS.  THIS PACKAGE ARRIVED IN WILMINGTON ON FLYT# 0151, 990AX.  THIS LAB PACK WAS MARKED "OVERWRAP FOR DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMEN SHIPMENTS".   AS A PRECAUTION, THE AREA INVOLVED WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED WITH BLEACH BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THE PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS SEALED AND BAGGED THE LAB PACK IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0038  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Defective Component or Device
column168: OUR DRIVER OPENED HIS TRAILER DOOR AT THE CUSTOMERS DOCK AND SMELLED A STRONG ODOR.  HE SAW SOME LEAKAGE FROM THE PRODUCT.  HE NOTIFIED OUR OS&D OPERATION.  DONNA CAME TO ME AND I HAD HER TELL THE DRIVER TO PULL THE TRAILER AWAY FROM THEIR DOCK AND LEAVE THE TRAILER DOOR OPEN AND WAIT FOR INSTRUCTIONS BUT TO NOT LET ANYONE IN HIS TRAILER.  I CALLED DIRECTOR OF SAFETY AND SENT SUPERVISOR TO SECURE & CALLED HMHTTC RESPONSE TEAM.  LEAKING WAS FROM THE GROMMET ON THE HANDLES OF THE PAILS.  HAZMAT TEAM SECURED LEAKER IN RECOVERY DRUM.  BROUGHT THE LOAD BACK TO THE TERMINAL PICTURES SENT TO DIRECTOR OF SAFETY (DIGITAL)
column169: THE PAILS LOOKED TO BE RUSTING IN PARTS.  PARTICULARY THE HANDLE CONNECTIORS AND THE CRIMPING AREAS OF THE LIOS.  LOOKS LIKE PRODUCT WAS IN THESE CONTAINERS FOR A LONG TIME.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX ON THURSDAY, 3/10 AS A CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORM-D.  WE REFUSED THE SHIPMENT BECAUSE THE DESTINATION WAS AN INTERNATIONAL LOCATION WHERE THE ICAO REGULATIONS SHOULD HAVE BEEN UTILIZED AND WE DON'T SERVICE THE TURKS WITH DANGEROUS GOODS SERVICE.  ON FRIDAY, 3/11, THE SHIPMENT WAS RE-OFFERED, ONLY THIS TIME THE SHIPMENT HAD NO DG MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  SCOTT GARDENER, A FEDEX DG SPECIALIST, RECOGNIZED THE PACKAGE ON THE SORT BELT, REMOVED IT FROM THE SORT AND NOTIFIED ME.  I HAVE SINCE NOTIFIED THE FAA IN MIA.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION IN HOLLYWOOD, FL.

JIM SWEENY, HEAD CLERK, REPORTED CONTAINER EMPU 285957, PLACARDED CORROSIVE, WAS NOTED LEAKING AND MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT PIT AT THE INTERMODAL RAMP, CITY OF INDUSTRY, CA.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND EN ROUTE.  MR. COOPER STATED TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL WOULD BE CALLED TO ASSIST WITH CLEAN UP.  AT 04:56 PM, MANAGER COOPER REQUESTED HE BE CONFERENCED WITH CHEMTREC FOR INFORMATION ON THE SHIPPER.  CHEMTREC, ADVISED CH ROBINSON, THE SHIPPER OF RECORD ON THE WAYBILL INFORMATION, WAS NOT A REGISTERED MEMBER OF CHEMTREC.  MANAGER COOPER ADVISED APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF 'STANNIC CHLORIDE SW 50%' HAD LEAKED FROM A LOOSE CLOSURE CAP ON ONE OF THE TOTES.  A TOTAL OF 8 TOTES WERE LOCATED AND IDENTIFIED AS CONTAINING THE STANNIC CHLORIDE ON THE BILLING INFORMATION WHICH INCORRECTLY IDENTIFIED THE PRODUCT AS 'O-METHYLBENZYL CHLORIDE' ON THE RAILROAD'S COMPUTER SYSTEM.  AS A RESULT, THE PRODUCT WAS MISDECLARED ON THE RAILROAD WAYBILL.  CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE REMAINING TOTES IDENTIFIED ALL THE TOP CLOSURE CAPS WERE LOOSE.  ONE TO TWO OUNCES OF PRODUCT WERE POOLED ON THE TOP RECESSED AREA AROUND THE CLOSURES OF EACH TOTE.  ALL OF THE LOOSE PRODUCT WAS REMOVED BY WIPING DOWN THE TOTES.  ALSO NOTED, THERE WAS ONLY A SINGLE 2X4 NAILED TO THE FLOOR AT THE REAR OF THE TOTES TO SECURE THE LOAD.  THIS IS NOT RECOMMENDED, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE6C FOR SECURING HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES FOR RAIL TRANSPORT.  CHEMTREC WAS ABLE TO LOCATE THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT AFTER A PACKING LIST WAS LOCATED WITHIN THE LOAD.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM MASON CORP. CONFIRMED THE PRODUCT WAS IN FACT STANNIC CHLORIDE, AND THAT THE TRANSPORTATION WAS ORIGINALLY SCHEDULED AS AN OVER THE ROAD MOVE, WHICH WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE LACK OF BLOCKING AND BRACING.  ONCE THE CLOSURE CAPS WERE SECURED, THE RESIDUE REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER, AND PROPER SECUREMENT WAS IN PLACE, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR OVER THE ROAD DELIVERY TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30AM ON MARCH 16TH 2005 DALTON BARLOW ARRIVED AT TOM THUMB STORE #135 6495 N W STREET PENSACOLA, FL, 32505.  DALTON POSITIONED HIS TRUCK TO BEGIN DROPPING FUEL AFTER REMOVING HIS FITTINGS.  DALTON GOT HIS SHORT HOSE OUT AND REALIZED THAT HIS TRUCK WAS POSITIONED TOO FAR FORWARD.  RATHER THAN REMOVING THE FITTINGS AND LOWERING THE JOHNNY BAR DALTON USED A WOODEN WEDGE IN THE JONNY BAR TO DISENGAGE THE TRAILER BRAKES, GOT INTO THE TRUCK RELEASED THE TRACTOR BRAKES AND ALLOWED THE TRUCK TO ROLL BACK TWO FEET.  WHEN DALTON GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK HE FAILED TO RESET THE TRACTOR BRAKES AND DID NOT REMOVE THE WEDGE THAT DISABLED THE JOHNNY BAR.  DALTON PROCEEDED TO HOOK UP HIS HOSE AND BEGAN DROPPING FUEL AT THIS TIME THE TRUCK STARTED TO ROLL.  DALTON RAN TO THE TRACTOR AND ENGAGED THE TRACTOR BRAKES BUT THE TRUCK ROLLED FAR ENOUGH TO BREAK THE FITTING AT THE DROP POINT AT PAVEMENT.  IT TOOK DALTON APPROXIMATELY 15 SECONDS TO RUN TO THE TRAILER AND PULL THE HANDLE ON THE DROP VALVE TO STOP THE FLOW OF FUEL.  APPROXIMATELY 75 GALLONS OF UNLEADED FUEL SPILLED.  DALTON CONTACTED KATHIE SHERRELL (TRANSPORTATION MANAGER) OF THE INCIDENT KATHIE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED SWS ENVIRONMENTAL FIRST RESPONSE.  BEFORE SWS RESPONDED DALTON PLACED ABSORBENT PADS IN THE FUEL PATHWAY BUT DO TO A HEAVY RAIN DURING AND AFTER THE SPILL FUEL FLOWED INTO A NEAR BY RETENTION POND.  WHEN SWS ARRIVED THEY WERE ABLE TO CLEAN UP THE ENTIRE SPILL.  SWS NOTIFIED THE STATE WARNING POINT OF THE INCIDENT AND FILED A DISCHARGE REPORT.  THIS WAS FOUND TO BE DRIVER ERROR AND THE DRIVER PRUPOSELY VIOLATED SAFETY PROCEDURES THEREFORE THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED.

column168: At approximately 2010 hours, while working in the Phoenix District, Switchman Bassem Hayek was injured while trying to put out a fire that was started by a leaking hydrogen peroxide tank car. When I interviewed Mr. Hayek he informed me that he was in the process of switching Seeler #1 track when the incident occurred. He informed me that the crew had went into Seeler #1 track and coupled up all the cars (including making air joints) then pulled the track out until the hind car (GATX 19661- a shipper to be brought back to Joliet) was on the phoenix lead at the bottom of the hifi. Mr. Hayek stated that after tying a handbrake on the subject car he cut away from it and pulled the balance of the cars into the clear on PHX 2 i:rack. The crew then lined the switches for the west end of the Phoenix yard into PHXi track. Once these switches were lined Hayek bled the subject car off, released the handbrake, and then rode the car down into PHX 1 track in order to control the cars speed (PHX 1 track was where the crew was building their outbound train). Mr. Hayek then walked back towards the west end of the Phoenix yard in order to do his next move bul: noticed some smoke coming from between the rails near the PHX 2 track switch. He stated that he threw dirt onto the smoking area until it. stopped smoking and then continued with his next move in order to switch Seeler #1 track. This move was to shove west out of PHX 2 track and into the Seeler 1&2 track lead where the crew would cut off three cars that were to eventually get respotted in Seeler #1 track (the cars that were getting cut off here were GATX 61179, UTLX 200600, and UTLX 200651). After cutting these cars off the crew pulled ahead until KCPX 17229 (another shipper to be brought back to Joliet) Was on the phoenix lead at the bottom of the hifi and then tied a hand brake on it and cut away just as they had done in the earlier move. After doing this the crew once again pulled the balance of the cars into the clear on PHX 2 track, lined the switches at the west end of the phoenix yard for PHX 1 track, and then bled the subject: car off and released the handbrake in order to allow the car to roliL into PHX 1 track where it would tie onto their outbound train (Mr. Hayek did not ride this car into PHX 1 track to control the speed as he usually only does that for loads and this car was an empty). Once this car made it into the clear on PHX 1 track Mr. Hayek began to line his train out of PHX 2 track and up the hill at the phoenix where he would tie onto KCPX 17223 for his next move (this car was to be spotted at the same spot that the cr he had just dropped onto his outbound train was spotted). However, when he lined the PHX 1 track switch and the Seeler 1&2 lead switch he saw flames coming from the area under the three cars that he had cut off on the Seeler 1&2 track lead. column168: DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION AT CSX TRANSPORTATIONS'S GENTILLY YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA, A FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION INSPPECTOR DISCOVERED TANK CAR, UTLX12487, RESIDUE, PHOSPHORIC ACID, HAD MANWAY SECURE BOLTS HANGING DOWN.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER IN NEW ORLEANS INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT 3 OF 6 MANWAY BOLTS WERE HANGING DOWN AND THE REMAING 3 MANWAY BOLTS WERE LESS THAN HAND TIGHT.  IT WAS NOT CERTAIN IF THERE HAD BEEN A PRODCUT RELEASE FROM THE UNSECURED MANWAY.  HE MADE ALL THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column168: AT 8:35AM, TUESDAY, MARCH 29, 2005: WHILE ON TRACK WAITING FOR YPPR52 TO CLEAR THE CHEMICAL COAST SECONDARY (IMMEDIATELY OUTSIDE CR;S PORT READING YARD FACILITY, SERVING YARD FOR CUSTOMER), PORT READING YARD CREW YPPR01 NOTIFIED YARDMASTER THAT TANK CAR TIL 320109, LOAD, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (ETHANOL, PETROLEUM DISTILLATES), WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AS YPPR52 PASSED THEM. NOTIFICATIONS MADE BY PORT READING YARDMASTER, IN ADDITION TO CONTACTING THE CONSIGNEE, MOTIVA ENTERPIRSES, SEWARD, NJ. CR S.T.O., MT. LAUREL, NJ, ALSO CONTACTED THE 24-HR. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER DISPLAYED ON THE WAYBILL (1-800-633-8253, "PROFESSIONAL EMERGECNY RESPONSE SERVICES") AND SPOKE WITH  "BRENT BAUER" AT 8:55AM;AND, THE NJ DEP ("OPERATOR 18", 10:13AM).    MR. T. FRYE OF MOTIVA ARRIVED AT APPOXIMATELY 9:00AM AND WAS ESCORTED TO WHERE THE TRAIN HAD COME TO A STOP.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LEAK WAS ORIGINATING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE DUE TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE CAP BEING OFF AND THE VALVE OPEN.  MR. FRYE CLOSED THE VALVE, STOPPING THE LEAK, AND SECURED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE CAP.  LEAK REPORTED STOPPED AT 9:03AM.    FURTHER INSPECTION BY CONRAIL;S R. CLOEDE, ASSISTANT SUPERINTENDENT; R. CAPARELLI, MANAGER CAR INSPECTION AND REPAIR; N. FERRONE, DIRECTOR RISK MANAGEMENT; AND REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES; R. GOULD; FOUND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET DETERIORATED.  VISIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE WAS ALSO FOUND ON TOP AND SIDES OF CAR.  GASKET REPLACED, MANWAY COVER SECURED, AND CAR OKAYED TO BE FORWARDED ON TO ORIGINIAL DESTINATION.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.    FURTHER INSPECTION OF 6 OTHER CARS (SAME SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE AND PRODUCT) FOUND IMPROPERLY PREPARED DUE TO THE SHIPPER'S SEA (ORANGE-COLORED "BNSF" SEALS) WERE NOT APPLIED THROUGH THE TOGGLE PIN FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLETS, SEVERAL BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE CAPS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  ALL EXCEPTIONS NOTED WERE CORRECTED PRIOR TO THE CARS BEING PERMITTED TO MOVE TO THE CUSTOMER.     AT THE REQUEST OF CONRAIL AND NORFOLK SOUTHER CORPORATION (FOR WHOM CONRAIL WAS DELIVERING TANK CAR), THE ARR-BOE INSPECTED THE ORIGINATING  FACILITY (TALL CORN ETHANOL, COON RAPIDS, IA) ON 3/31/05, FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION AND FUTURE COMPLIANCE TO AVOID RECURRENCES OF STATE DEFICIENCIES.  THE AAR-BOE REPORT OF THIS INSPECTION WILL BE FORWARDED WHEN RECEIVED BY CONRAIL.

column42: AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUEFIED OR AMMONIA SOLUTIONS RELATIVE DENSITY LESS THAN .880 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 50 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: ON MARCH 29,2005, BOB KERSSCHNER, A TRUCK DRIVER WITH LAROCHE INDUSTRIES, WAS AT THE OSRAM SYLVANIA PLAN IN YORK, PENNSYLVANIA TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA INTO THEIR STORAGE TANK.  ACCORDING TO OSRAM'S DELIVERY PROCEDURES, BOB HAD RE-CIRCULATED THE CONTENT OF HIS TRAILER AND JUST FINISHED TAKING A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT TO BE DELIVERED.  AS HE WAS CHECKING ALL THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER TO ASSURE THAT THEY WERE IN THE PROPER ALIGNMENT, BOB INADVERTENTLY CRACKED THE VAPOR VALVE (WHILE CHECKING TO SEE IF IT WAS CLOSE) FOR A MOMENT ALLOWING RE-CONDENSED VAPOR FROM THE RISER TUBE TO ENTER THE VAPOR HOSE THAT WAS LAYING IN THE HOSE TROUGH OF THE TRAILER.  THIS HOSE WAS PLUGGED AND SECURED IN THE HOSE TROUGH.  APPARENTLY THE PLUG ON THE END OF THE HOSE WAS NOT 100% TIGHT, AND ALLOWED THE AMMMONIA TO ESCAPE TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  AS SOON AS BOB REALIZED THAT TAMMONIA WAS ESCAPING TO THE ATMOSPHERE HE PUT THE END OF THE VAPOR HOSE INTO A BUCKET OF WATER TO CAPTURE THE AMMONIA FROM THE HOSE.  ACCORDING TO BOB KERSCHNER, THIS ENTIRE PROCESS, THE TIME HE CRACKED THE VAPOR VALVE TO THE TIME HE PUT THE END OF THE HOSE INTO THE BUCKET OF WATER, TOOK LESS THAN 30 SECONDS AND THAT ONLY ABOUT AN OUNCE OR TWO OF LIQUID WAS RELEASED TO THE STMOSPHERE.   THE CONTRIBUTING FACTORS TO THIS RELEASE WAS:  1-THE VAOPR VALVE ON THE TRAILER SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN OPENED AT ANY TIME DURING THE UNLOADING AT OSRAM SYLVANIA.  2-THE PLUG ON THE END OF THE HOSES SHOULD BE CHECKED FOR TIGHTNESS PRIOR TO LEAVING THE YARD IN PLMERTON, WHERE THE TRUCK ORIGINATED.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO BE TAKEN:  1-BOB KERSCHNER AND ALL THE DRIVERS AT OUR PLAMERTON FACILITY WILL REVIEW THE OSRAM SYLVANIA'S UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  2-BOB KERSCHNER AND ALL THE DRIVERS AT OUR PLAMERTON FACILITY WILL REVIEW OUR SAFE JOB PROCEDURE, A-03, UNLOADING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARGO TRUCK.  TARGET DATES:  THE REVIEW OF ALL PROCEDURES MENTION ABOVE WILL BE COMPLETED BY THE NEXT DELIVERY INTO OSRAM SYLVANIA WHICH IS PROJECTED TO BE AROUND APRIL 15, 2005.  I WILL CERTIFY ALL PROCEDURAL TRAINING.  RUSSELL ZINTAK.
