column168: A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RELEASE WAS REPORTED FROM TANKCAR GATX 10969 WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED.  LESS THAN ONE QUART OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR, WITH LESS THAN ONE CUP HITTING THE GROUND.  THERE WERE NO REPORTS OF INJURIES OR EXPOSURES.  MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RESPONDED AND HIS INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE RUPTURE DISK ON THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE HAD FAILED.  MR. REIMERS REPLACED THE RUPTURE DISK AND DECONTAMINATED THE CAR AND THE GROUND WITH A VINEGAR SOLUTION.

column168: TANKCAR SAUX 807 WAS REPORTED LEAKING ON 03/29/2005.  AFTER INVESTIGATION BY SPECIAL AGENT MIKE KOSCINSKI, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WAS LEAKING.  MR. KOSCINSKI CONTACTED MARK REIMERS, REGIONAL MGR - CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY FOR FURTHER ASSISTANCE.  MR. REIMERS AND MR. KOSCINSKI CONTACTED BOTH THE SHIPPER, KOCH INDUSTRIES, AND THE CONSIGNEE, CONTINENTAL NITROGEN, FOR ASSISTANCE.  BOTH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE SENT REPRESENTATIVES TO THE YARD TO ASSIST WITH THE RELEASE.  MR. REIMERS CONTACTED MARK MADAY, MGR-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, AND DISPATCHED HIM TO ST. PAUL TO RELIEVE MR. KOSCINSKI.  MR. MADAY ARRIVED ON SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM AND HIS INSPECTION VERIFIED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  HE ADVISED THAT AN ATTEMPT TO REPAIR THE O-RINGS WOULD TAKE PLACE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 7:30 PM. MR. MADAY REPORTED THAT ATTEMPTS TO REPAIR THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE WHILE THE CAR WAS UNDER PRESSURE WERE UNSUCESSFUL.  MR. MADAY STATED THAT THE CONSIGNEE, CONTINENTAL NITROGEN, HAS MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR HULCHER SERVICES TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT OFF THE CAR INTO TANKER TRUCKS.  TRANSFER OPERATIONS, WERE TO CONTINUE THROUGHOUT THE NIGHT, AND THE OPERATION WAS TO BE COMPLETED, TO INCLUDE PURGING OF THE CAR, BY 5:00 PM THURSDAY.  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 PM, 03/31/05, MR MADAY REPORTED THAT HE WAS ABLE TO REPAIR THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AFTER PRESSURE IN THE CAR HAD DROPPED BELOW 25 PSI DURING THE TRANSFER OPERATION.  TRANSFER AND PURGING OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED.  MR. MADAY STATED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN PURGED DOWN TO 1 PSI, RESECURED, AND TAGGED "DO NOT LOAD - HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS".  MR. MADAY ALSO STATED THAT THE CAR WAS BEING RELEASED BACK TO THE SHIPPER/OWNER AS A "RESIDUE-LAST CONTAINED" CAR, AND THAT THEY (THE SHIPPER/OWNER) WOULD COORDINATE ADDITIONAL REPAIRS/INSPECTION OF TANKCAR SAUX 807.

ON MARCH 4, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 6:45 A.M. CST, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM WAS CROSSING RAILROAD TRACKS NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF 142ND STREET AND PAXTON AVENUE GOING TO THE ASHLAND CHEMICAL FACILITY WHEN THE TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY A CSX FREIGHT TRAIN.  THE IMPACT RIPPED THE TRAILER OPEN.  THE TRAILER CONTAINED 55 55-GALLON POLY DRUMS OF ACRYLIC ACID.  FOUR (4) OF THE DRUMS WERE RUPTURED FROM THE IMPACT AND RELEASED THEIR CONTENTS ONTO THE SOIL.  THE ACRYLIC ACID MIGRATED TO A NEARBY DRAINAGE DITCH WHICH CONTAINED STANDING RAIN WATER.  THE CALUMET CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENT AND PERSONNEL FROM ASHLAND CHEMICALS INITIALLY RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  PERIMETER AROUND THE TRUCK WAS CORDONED OFF FOR SAFETY PRECAUTIONS.  CSX DISPATCHED AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CREW FROM HULCHER SERVICES TO ASSESS THE SITE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:53 A.M. CST, MR. CHUCK WHITE WITH KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES CONTACTED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP ON BEHALF OF KLLM.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED THE DRIVER OF THE SUBJECT TRACTOR-TRAILER TO GAIN ADDITIONAL INFORMATION ON THE RELEASE.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSESS THE SITE AND UPDATE THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER.  AT THE TIME, CES WAS UNAWARE THAT HULCHER SERVICES WAS ONSITE TO REPRESENT CSX.  THE PROJECT MANAGER FROM HAZCHEM ARRIVED ON-SITE AND MET WITH REPRESENTATIVES ON-SITE.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED MR. ED COOK WITH CSX TO COMMUNICATE THE WORK PLAN.  CES WAS GOING TO PLACE HULCHER UNDER CONTACT TO ASSIST HAZCHEM WITH THE COMPLETION OF THE CLEANUP.  AT THIS TIME, HULCHER AND HAZCHEM WORKED TOGETHER IN A JOINT CLEANUP OPERATION.  THE RESPONSE CREWS DONNED LEVEL C PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT (PPE) PRIOR TO ENTERING THE HOT ZONE AREA.  ONCE INSIDE THE HOT ZONE AREA, THE CREW USED A CRANE TO BEGAN REMOVAL OF THE POLY DRUMS.  A SOIL BERM WAS BUILT ALONG THE DRAINAGE DITCH TO CONTAIN THE RELEASED ACID.  ONCE MOST OF THE DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER, A WRECKER SERVICE (WES SERVICES) WAS USED TO MOVE THE TRAILER TO ALLOW THE RESPONSE CREWS TO GET TO THE REMAINING DRUMS.  THE DRUMS THAT WERE NOT DAMAGED WERE PLACED INTO TWO TRUCKS FOR TRANSPORTATION TO PCI FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO OVERPACKS FOR DISPOSAL.  ONCE THE DRUM WORK WAS COMPLETED, THE TRAILER WAS DISAPTCHED TO REMOVE THE IMPACTED SOILS.  THE IMPACTED SOILS WERE PLACED INTO TWO (2) ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS AND STORED ONSITE UNTIL PROFILING AND DISPOSAL COULD BE COMPLETED.

column168: RANDY KELLER, YARD MASTER, REPORTED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAK AT THE HOFFMAN YARD, ST. PAUL, MN.  MR. KELLER STATED HOPPER CAR CRDX 6046 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT ON TRACKS TWENTY-EIGHT AND TWENTY-NINE.  OPERATOR HARRIS, ST. PAUL POLICE DEPARTMENT, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED LOCAL EMS OFFICIALS WERE EN ROUTE.  MICHAEL KOSCINSKI, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MARK MADAY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONTRACTED HULCHER SERVICES TO PERFORM REMEDIATION.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE LEAK WAS THE RESULT OF THE HATCHES NOT PROPERLY SEALED IN PLACE.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS TRANSPORTED TO A STAGING AREA NEAR THE RIP-TRACK WITH PLASTIC ON THE GROUND.  SPILLED PRODUCT WAS DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
